    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "## Summary\n\nCython 3.3.0a1 (and current master) generates invalid C++ code when a `unique_ptr` attribute is compared to `NULL` in a boolean context (e.g., `if` statement or similar). The generated code casts `NULL` to `unique_ptr`, which is ambiguous with GCC 14.\n\n## Minimal Reproducer\n\n```cython\n# repro.pyx\nfrom libcpp.memory cimport unique_ptr\n\ncdef extern from *:\n    \"\"\"\n    struct MyStruct {\n        int value;\n    };\n    \"\"\"\n    cdef cppclass MyStruct:\n        int value\n\ncdef class Wrapper:\n    cdef unique_ptr[MyStruct] c_obj\n\ncpdef bint check_not_null(Wrapper w):\n    if w.c_obj != NULL:\n        return True\n    return False\n```\n\nCompile with:\n```bash\ncython --cplus repro.pyx -o repro.cxx\ng++ -std=c++20 -fPIC -shared -I$(python -c \"import sysconfig; print(sysconfig.get_path('include'))\") repro.cxx -o repro.so\n```\n\n## Error\n\n```\nrepro.cxx: error: call of overloaded 'unique_ptr(NULL)' is ambiguous\n  __pyx_t_1 = (__pyx_v_w->c_obj != ((std::unique_ptr<MyStruct> )NULL));\n                                                                 ^~~~\n/usr/include/c++/14/bits/unique_ptr.h:353:19: note: candidate: 'constexpr std::unique_ptr<_Tp, _Dp>::unique_ptr(std::nullptr_t)'\n/usr/include/c++/14/bits/unique_ptr.h:311:9: note: candidate: 'std::unique_ptr<_Tp, _Dp>::unique_ptr(pointer)'\n```\n\n## Environment\n\n- **Cython 3.3.0a1 / master** — FAILS\n- **Cython 3.2.5** — PASSES (generates `(__pyx_v_w->c_obj != NULL)` directly)\n- **GCC 14.3.0**\n- **C++ standard**: C++20\n\n## Generated Code Comparison\n\n### Cython 3.2.5 (correct)\n```cpp\n__pyx_t_1 = ((__pyx_v_w->c_obj != NULL) != 0);\n```\n`NULL` is passed directly to `unique_ptr::operator!=`, which works fine.\n\n### Cython 3.3.0a1 (broken)\n```cpp\n__pyx_t_1 = (__pyx_v_w->c_obj != ((std::unique_ptr<MyStruct> )NULL));\n```\n`NULL` is explicitly cast to `unique_ptr`, which requires constructing a `unique_ptr` from `NULL`. This is ambiguous because GCC's `NULL` (`__null`) matches both:\n- `unique_ptr(pointer)` (pointer = `MyStruct*`)\n- `unique_ptr(nullptr_t)`\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe regression was introduced by commit `23581d608` (\"Always evaluate comparisons as bint if that is the expected result\").\n\nIn `coerce_to_boolean`, the method now unconditionally sets `is_temp = True`. With `is_temp = True`, `generate_evaluation_code` takes the `generate_operation_code()` path, which computes a `common_type` and uses `result_as(common_type)`:\n\n```python\ncommon_type = type1  # unique_ptr<MyStruct>\ncode2 = operand2.result_as(common_type)  # casts NULL to unique_ptr → broken!\n```\n\nSince `analyse_cpp_comparison()` already coerces operands to the correct argument types of the resolved operator, the subsequent `result_as(common_type)` in `generate_operation_code` is redundant and harmful for C++ comparisons.\n\n## Workaround\n\nIn user code, avoid `ptr != NULL` and use truthiness instead:\n\n```cython\n# Instead of:\nif w.c_obj != NULL:\n\n# Use:\nif w.c_obj:\n```\n\nThis avoids the comparison codepath entirely.\n",
